Child Stunting : Story of an hidden crisis

Sources : UN, WHO, UNICEF

Author

Marie BELLAN

Published

April 25, 2025

What is child stunting?

Today, one in five children under the age of five falls short of WHO growth standardsâa condition known as stunting.

While malnutrition is often considered as the main cause of stunting, in most cases we observe a more complex narrative. Indeed, repeated infections, contaminated water sources, entrenched poverty, and limited maternal education play as big a role as acute malnutrition.

This challenge is multidimensional, affecting the physical but also the cognitive development of more than 149 millions of children in 2022 (WHO, 2024) and putting them in danger.

Code 
import pandas as pd
import plotnine
from plotnine import (
    ggplot,
    aes,
    geom_point,
    geom_smooth,
    labs,
    theme_bw
)
df_stunting = pd.read_excel("unicef_indicator_2_quarto_vo.xlsx")
df_u5mr = pd.read_excel("U5MR_corrected.xlsx")
df_stunting_total = df_stunting[df_stunting['sex'] == 'Total'].copy()
df_stunting_total.rename(columns={'time_period': 'year', 'stunting_prevalence_pourcentage': 'stunting_prevalence'}, inplace=True)
df_stunting_total = df_stunting_total[['country', 'year', 'stunting_prevalence']]
df_u5mr.rename(columns={'year': 'year', 'U5MR_estimate': 'u5mr'}, inplace=True)
df_u5mr = df_u5mr[['country', 'year', 'u5mr']]
df_merged = pd.merge(df_stunting_total, df_u5mr, on=['country', 'year'], how='inner')
(ggplot(df_merged, aes(x='stunting_prevalence', y='u5mr'))
    + geom_point(color='#ADD8E6')
    + geom_smooth(method='lm', se=False, color='black')
    + labs(
        title='Relationship between Under-Five Stunting Prevalence and Under-Five Mortality Rate',
        x='Avg. Under-Five Stunting Prevalence (%)',
        y='Under-Five Mortality (for 1000 children)'
    )
    + theme_bw()
    + coord_fixed(ratio=0.1)
    + theme_bw()
    + theme(figure_size=(9,5)))

The most alarming consequence of stunting is the significantly increased risk of mortality. Stunted children have a weaker immune system, which makes them more susceptible to infectious diseases and other aggravating environmental factors.

Who is affected?

Code 
import pandas as pd
import plotnine
from plotnine import (
    ggplot,
    aes,
    geom_bar,
    facet_wrap,
    labs,
    theme_bw,
    theme,
    scale_fill_manual,
)
data = {
    'World_region_by_UN': ['African States', 'Asia-Pacific States', 'Eastern European States',
                          'Latin American and Caribbean States', 'Western European and other States'],
    'Female': [31.69, 24.89, 10.57, 17.23, 2.24],
    'Male': [36.48, 26.90, 11.76, 19.88, 2.54]
}
df = pd.DataFrame(data)
df_melted = df.melt(id_vars='World_region_by_UN', value_vars=['Female', 'Male'],
                    var_name='Sex', value_name='Stunting Prevalence (%)')
(ggplot(df_melted, aes(x='World_region_by_UN', y='Stunting Prevalence (%)', fill='Sex'))
    + geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge')
    + labs(
        title='Gender distribution of Under-Five Child Stunting across UN World Regions',
        x='UN World Region',
        y='Average Stunting Prevalence (%)'
    )
    + scale_fill_manual(values={"Female": "#ADD8E6", "Male": "#00008B"})
    + theme_bw()
    + theme(plot_title=element_text(
         size=12,
         hjust=0.5,
         color="#333333"
     ),
     axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=45, hjust=1)
 )
    + theme(figure_size=(8, 6))
)

Several studies have been conducted to identify if sex is a risk factor for stunting. It seems that boys are slightly more at risk of stunting, as they seem to be more susceptible to infectious diseases.

Now, we will study the geographical repartition of under five child stunting cases. The map below shows the prevalence of stunting in children under five around the world between 2000 and 2022.

Did you know ?

In 2012, the World Health Organization (WHO) defined any country with a stunting prevalence rate above 5% as âout of trackâ.

Code 
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gp
import plotnine
from plotnine import (
    ggplot,
    aes,
    geom_map,
    scale_fill_gradient2,
    labs,
    coord_fixed,
    theme_bw,
    theme,
    element_text
)
df_stunting = pd.read_excel("unicef_indicator_2_quarto_vo.xlsx")
df_stunting['time_period'] = pd.to_numeric(df_stunting['time_period'], errors='coerce').astype('Int64')
df_stunting_total = df_stunting[
    (df_stunting['sex'] == 'Total') & (df_stunting['time_period'] >= 2000) & (df_stunting['time_period'] <= 2022)
].copy()
df_stunting_avg = df_stunting_total.groupby('country')['stunting_prevalence_pourcentage'].mean().reset_index()
world = gp.read_file("https://public.opendatasoft.com/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/world-administrative-boundaries/exports/shp")
world = world.rename(columns={'name_long': 'name'})
df_merged = world.merge(df_stunting_avg, left_on='name', right_on='country', how='left')
(ggplot(data=df_merged, mapping=aes(fill='stunting_prevalence_pourcentage', map_id='name'))
    + geom_map()
    + scale_fill_gradient2(
        low='lightblue',
        mid='#D6FFFF',
        high='darkblue',
        midpoint=5,
        name='Average Stunting Prevalence (%)',
        na_value='grey')
    + labs(
        title="Worldwide repartition of Under-Five Stunting Prevalence (2000-2022)",
        subtitle="Countries in grey have not enough data to be accurately evaluated",
        caption="Source: UNICEF",
        x="Longitude",
        y="Latitude",
        fill="Average Stunting Prevalence (%)"
    )
    + theme_bw()
    + theme(figure_size=(10,5)))

Indeed, as stunting is a consequence of chronic malnutrition, untreated infections, unsafe water sources, limited access to education and healthcare, and severe poverty, we can find high stunting prevalence in countries with low income and high instability. This explains why we can observe the highest concentration of stunting among under five children on the African continent and in South Asia.
The five countries with the highest stunting prevalence rates (average calculated between 2012 and 2022) are :
- Burundi;
- Timor-Leste;
- Yemen;
- Guatemala;
- Madagascar.

They all present a rate superior to 40%.

These countries are located in low income regions where progress has been particularly slow with no quick fix solutions. Conflicts, climate vulnerability, weak governance structures, and limited healthcare systems make any international intervention harder to plan & execute, encouraging stagnant stunting rates.

Is there still hope?

Code 
import pandas as pd
import plotnine
from plotnine import (
    ggplot,
    aes,
    geom_line,
    labs,
    theme_bw,
    theme
)
df = pd.read_excel("unicef_indicator_2_quarto_vo.xlsx")
df['time_period'] = pd.to_numeric(df['time_period'], errors='coerce')
df_grouped = df.groupby('time_period')['stunting_prevalence_pourcentage'].mean().reset_index()
df_grouped = df_grouped.rename(columns={'stunting_prevalence_pourcentage': 'average_stunting_prevalence'})
(ggplot(df_grouped, aes(x='time_period', y='average_stunting_prevalence'))
    + geom_line(color='darkblue')
    + labs(
        title='Evolution of Worldwide Under five Stunting Prevalence Over Time',
        x='Year',
        y='Average Stunting Prevalence (%)'
    )
    + theme_bw()
    + theme(figure_size=(8, 4))
)

Globally, there has been a clear decrease in the prevalence of stunting over the past two decades. This was achieved thanks to coordinated international efforts that committed to provide a better access to food, water and general maternal health & hygiene. However, despite the significant progress, we can observe on the graph that recent years have seen a resurgence of stunting cases. This could be explained by the apparition of new violent conflicts such as the Russian-Ukrainian war, or the current bombing of Gaza. This shows that efforts to reduce stunting are still essential to protect children.

The WHO and UNICEF have now set up a global objective to reduce the number of stunted children under five by 40% by 2025. To achieve this, countries should implement a comprehensive strategy that include interventions in nutrition, health, education and hygiene.

While significant challenges persist, this global progress proves that with continued collaboration we could meet WHO and UNICEFâs targets.
